A lot of young people today choose not to drive or get their licenses, but back in the day, just a decade or so ago, everyone used to do it. Jason Genova was literally retarded and still used to drive to the gym every day in his mother's car even if he often missed the street.

Dr. Ray Peat had an anecdote about some guy who had gone almost fully blind and still somehow kept driving his car around town basically being unable to see the road or other cars. In the 2000s you could be blind and retarded and still had to drive everywhere in your car.

Who is Otalora? He is a man who lives under a political system he does not understand, where power is occult and no one knows who is actually in charge. Even the knife fight which he saves Bandeira in turns out to be "a fantasy". His world is dominated by spectacle and illusion.

One thing I just noticed in Borges' story "The Dead Man" (1946) is that the closing scene happens on the "commotion of the closing night of the year 1894", which is 1984 rearranged. It was published before Orwell's book, which probably means it's a reference to Chesterton's 1984.

The entire story makes sense if you see it as just "Borges' 1984". "The Napoleon of Notting Hill" was simply published as "Chesterton's 1984" in Japan üáØüáµ, titles like that are never a coincidence, like Huxley's book being translated as "The Best of All Possible Worlds" in France.
The Japanese cover was apparently made by Hayao Miyazaki and is incredibly cute, makes you smile just looking at it even if you don't know the story.

When H. G. Wells and his son visited Ivan Pavlov in the USSR, Wells' son said it was like spending an entire day outside of the Soviet Union. Dr. Pavlov's family had a governess, his laboratory was working, science was done, etc. Galkovsky had an interesting comment about this.

If they were outside the USSR, what was the place they were visiting? It wasn't merely the past or the real Russia as it existed previously. It was a slice of the global republic of scientists, a vision of the future World Order. Pavlov was a prototype of the coming ruling class.
